          "label": "<p>A young man develops haemolytic anaemia after being prescribed primaquine for ma</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A young man develops haemolytic anaemia after being prescribed primaquine for malaria. Which biochemical defect best explains his red cell fragility?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Deficient NADPH production, leading to reduced glutathione depletion</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. G6PD deficiency impairs the oxidative phase of the HMP shunt, lowering NADPH and therefore reduced glutathione, leaving red cells defenceless against oxidative stress from primaquine.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Deficient aldolase B activity causing fructose-1-phosphate accumulation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Aldolase B deficiency causes hereditary fructose intolerance with liver damage and hypoglycaemia, not drug-triggered haemolysis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Deficient galactose-1-phosphate uridylyl transferase</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This enzyme deficiency causes classic galactosaemia (cataracts, liver damage, intellectual disability), not haemolysis after primaquine.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Excessive sorbitol accumulation via aldose reductase</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The polyol pathway causes osmotic injury in diabetic cataracts, retinopathy, and neuropathy — not primaquine-induced haemolysis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Trace the logic: primaquine is an oxidant → red cells need reduced glutathione → glutathione needs NADPH → NADPH comes from the HMP shunt via G6PD."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly. The HMP shunt supplies NADPH, which keeps glutathione reduced and protects red cells from oxidants like primaquine, dapsone, and fava beans."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
